# Python Port Plan — Step 04_api_client

## Goal

Port `week1_baseline/ruby/04_api_client` (the `Client` class — real HTTP
POST to the active backend's API, with retry/backoff on transient failures
and retryable status codes) to Python at
`week1_baseline/python/04_api_client`. Same conventions as prior steps —
see [`docs/plans/python_port/00_config`](00_config) for the full rationale;
this doc covers what's new for this step.

## Decisions carried forward (unchanged)

| Question | Decision |
|---|---|
| Port fidelity | Literal mirror of the Ruby architecture |
| Ruby vs Python | Run alongside each other; Ruby stays untouched *except* real bug fixes explicitly authorized |
| Tooling | `uv` + `pyproject.toml` |
| Python package name | `boukensha` |
| Copy-forward | Byte-identical-Ruby-source files copied from the prior step's already-fixed Python file, not re-derived |
| **No third-party HTTP library** | Ruby's `Client` deliberately uses only `net/http` (stdlib) — the README says explicitly "This is intentional — the HTTP call itself is trivial and should be visible, not hidden behind a library." The Python port uses `urllib.request` (stdlib), not `requests`, for the same reason. |

## New for this step: a real behavior change to the acceptance test

Every prior step's acceptance test was **byte-for-byte diff of Ruby vs.
Python launcher output**. This step makes a real network call to a real
LLM API — the response includes a fresh response ID and freshly-generated
model text on every call, so a byte-diff of the full output is
structurally impossible here, not just inconvenient. **Decided with the
user (2026-07-22):**

- **One live round-trip per language**, using a real `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`
  (already present in the repo root's gitignored `.env` — sourced directly
  into the shell environment for the verification run, never copied into
  any tracked file or printed). Confirms the client genuinely completes an
  end-to-end call and prints a JSON response with the **same top-level key
  shape** (not identical values — `id`, `type`, `role`, `content`,
  `stop_reason`, `usage` etc.), not just that it doesn't crash.
- **A deliberately-invalid-key run**, also live, for both languages. `401`
  is not in `RETRYABLE_STATUS_CODES`, so it fails immediately (1 attempt,
  no retries) with a real `ApiError` — this is a free, reproducible way to
  verify the error-handling path against a real server response, without
  spending real output tokens. The exact `ApiError` message *shape*
  (`"API request failed after {n} attempt(s) ({code}): {body}"`) is
  compared between languages, since the failure is deterministic (both hit
  a real 401 immediately).
- **Retry/backoff timing and the transient-error path are not
  network-tested** (they'd need deliberately flaky infrastructure to
  trigger for real, which is out of scope for a tutorial step) — verified
  by direct code reading against the Ruby source line-by-line instead,
  same rigor the code-review pass already applies to every step.

Everything deterministic from prior steps — request payload construction,
header building, backend model tables — was already parity-tested in
`03_prompt_builder` and doesn't change here (`Client` just wraps
`PromptBuilder`, it doesn't touch payload construction itself).

